        "timestamp": "2021-09-17 10:24:03.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nLet me know if you have any remarks regarding the cfg file name/location/content.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "8dd5ddf968c9d18a6ce6c30c867b2d20f99cc4c8",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 7353,
          "name": "Marcin Wilk",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "m.wilk@samsung.com",
          "username": "mwilk"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-09-17 13:52:57.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1\n\n> Patch Set 4:\n> \n> Let me know if you have any remarks regarding the cfg file name/location/content.\n\nHow about changing default location of the resources.cfg from /etc/default/resources.cfg to /opt/onap/resources.cfg? Just to explicitly emphasize that this is ONAP related.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "25ba1ab00fa7cbd5100a58b0785cc4e4f4fe49f3",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5097,
          "name": "Bartek Grzybowski",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "b.grzybowski@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "bgrzybowski"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2021-09-20 07:12:30.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1\n> \n> > Patch Set 4:\n> > \n> > Let me know if you have any remarks regarding the cfg file name/location/content.\n> \n> How about changing default location of the resources.cfg from /etc/default/resources.cfg to /opt/onap/resources.cfg? Just to explicitly emphasize that this is ONAP related.\n\napp_data_path can be set to any arbitrary location, if it's not get set to a path with /opt/onap prefix wouldn't it be vague to have that cfg file in hardcoded path of /opt/onap?",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "7c80bd367725ae7e99a8d7549397d6f140cb63e2",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5335,
          "name": "Krystian  Kedron",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "k.kedron@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "krystian"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-09-20 11:51:53.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "e5fa4e6dee442349f77aea107f827b2003456053",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 7353,
          "name": "Marcin Wilk",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "m.wilk@samsung.com",
          "username": "mwilk"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2021-09-23 09:10:19.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> Patch Set 4:\n> \n> > Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1\n> > \n> > > Patch Set 4:\n> > > \n> > > Let me know if you have any remarks regarding the cfg file name/location/content.\n> > \n> > How about changing default location of the resources.cfg from /etc/default/resources.cfg to /opt/onap/resources.cfg? Just to explicitly emphasize that this is ONAP related.\n> \n> app_data_path can be set to any arbitrary location, if it's not get set to a path with /opt/onap prefix wouldn't it be vague to have that cfg file in hardcoded path of /opt/onap?\n\nCould be. My point was to potentially avoid confusion about /etc/default/resources.cfg which, for an unware user, might seem to be related to some 'system wide resource configuration (whatever that would be)'. It doesn't make a big difference for me. If you feel that /etc/default location is better - stick to it.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
